There is no doubting the place"s natuarl beauty. However the water is often filthy and the place is overun with us - tourists.

We did a trip that involved 2 overnights and at the end of the first day we were thinking of heading off in the morning and cutting it short. At one point we counted 40 tourist boats excluding the high powered speed boats screaming round the part of bay we were in.
However the 2nd day was far nicer. We had the chance to swim as well as kayak around a fishing village and lovely lagoon. We would recommend staying for the 2 overnights. Thisd means you get to appreciate the place away from the crowds (we were there off season)>
if you are trying to sqeeze a day trip in from Hanoi you may be very disapointed. If the tours are not better managed and the waters cleaned up this place is going to tragically ruined. UNESCO need to get a grip of the Vietnamese authorities.
Written March 12, 2010
Daithi85
Mayo30 contributions
4.0 of 5 bubbles
Could be a wonder of the world but grossly overtouristed and badly littered waters
Halong Bay's reputation sets it a hard task in meeting the expectations of visitors and we had looked forward to this trip for 4 months. We booked in advance with Sinh tourist cafe in Hoi An (the 3 day, 2 night option with a deluxe sticker slapped on it for $80) and found ourselves being dropped from Hanoi to the charming Marguerite boat. The staff there were friendly and courteous and the food, mostly local seafood, was excellent. The cabins were fantastic: clean with roomy ensuite, TV, dvd player, minibar, bowl of fruit. Our only bone to pick was at check out when they insisted we had drank three bottles of water from the minibar when we had drank one (there were only two to begin with instead of the usual four) and were a little bit stubborn about it.
The bay itself has reduced visibility in February because of the misty and overcast weather that descends on it. It is still obscenely beautiful. The big downer, though, is that the water in the bay is highly littered and in most parts unswimmable. This is partly due to the vast quantities of tourists being ferried about on it every day in hordes of boats.
The paradise cave docking area resembles a Hanoi traffic jam with boats hooting horns and banging into each other in the melee. The caves, while beautiful, have graffiti in parts and no effort is made to keep tourists from touching formations, which damages their development.
We spent a night on Cat Ba island, the village there being composed mostly of hotels. It is a good jump-off point for many of the more interesting tours in Halong Bay. It has one or two challenging treks which should not be attempted in rubber thongs, particularly if there has been rain creating a muddy slick on the ground.
Halong Bay, by rights, should be the type of attraction that only receives five stars from everyone. However it is rapidly being spoiled by unchecked development and overtouristing and it is a tide that will become difficult to reverse should it be allowed to continue over the next decade.
Written February 13, 2010
Johann&Sandra
8,376 contributions
Kayaking in a Sewage Lagoon - Never Did That Before.
Halong Bay is a must-do if you are in Northern Vietnam. It is very beautiful. For the best experience, definitely do the 2 night junk cruise though. We did 1 night and with the 8-hour round-trip drive from Hanoi, it was just too stressful. Still worth it, but would have been much more worth it if we had another night. The landscape is spectacular, though if you've ever been to Guilin or Yangshuo in China, you'll recognize the Karst Mountain formations. Don't bother with a day trip - without the feeling of being out on the water, this is too much driving for too little payoff. Make sure to allow the time you need. This is not a place for a quick "I've been there" photo-op, you won't enjoy that - but you will enjoy being out on the bay for a couple nights aboard a junk. They all include shore excursions such as the caves, which are much better than we expected, and kayaking on the bay, which was nice except for the pollution (read below), and also an excursion to a beach or something like that for the third day.
The only downside besides the drive from Hanoi is how polluted the water is. It's downright disgusting to kayak through sewage and garbage, make sure you have your hepatitis shots up to date and shower thoroughly immediately afterward. The first day, we saw almost no garbage on the water and were pleasantly surprised. However, the next morning, we looked over the railing on our junk and saw the crew throwing garbage into the water, then discharging sewage into the water, leaving a nasty trail of filth as we left our secluded cove where we'd spent the night. I thought at first maybe it was just us doing this, but as we kayaked through the caves, and the water was brown and bubbly, with garbage floating everywhere, we were repulsed. The rest of the day as we cruised around, it was hard not to notice the piles of garbage and sewage spills floating in the bay, so I guess it wasn't just our junk polluting the bay. There is no current to speak of, so the filth doesn't disipate. Throughout the time we were in northern Vietnam, the government is conducting a campaign to have Halong Bay be one of the new 7 wonders of the natural world. It boggles my mind to think that they realize they have a natural wonder, yet continue to allow this unabashed polluting of their single biggest natural tourist attraction.
Despite the nastiness we experienced during the kayaking and cruise on the second day, and not being able to swim for fear of hepatitis, we did enjoy our cruise - just make sure you do your homework about the junk you choose, as they are not all made equal. A nice experience, they have just got to get serious about regulating the junks and their polluting.
Written November 11, 2009
